    "recap_headline": "",
    "recap_text": "Coral Gables, Fla. --\nKnotted at 4-4 entering the bottom of the seventh, Creighton surrendered five runs in the frame to drop the series opener at Miami 9-4 on Friday, March 20. The loss evened the Bluejays record at 9-9, while Miami moved to 16-6.\nCreighton and Miami traded runs in the first, fourth and fifth frames.\nThe Bluejays opened the game with back-to-back singles from\nRocco Gump\nand\nTeddy Deters\n. After a ground ball double play,\nBen North\npicked up his squad with an RBI single to right. Miami answered with a one-out solo home run from Daniel Cuvet to right.\nCreighton went back on top in the fourth as\nConnor Capece\nlined an RBI double down the left field line to bring home North, who opened the frame with a single. The Hurricanes answered immediately with an RBI ground out from Michael Torres.\nOnce more in the fifth the Jays surged in front, getting a leadoff walk from\nLew Rice\nand a one-out RBI double from Deters. Cuvet, however, responded with his second long ball of the game to bring the score to 3-3.\nTrailing 4-3 as the game moved to the top of the seventh,\nNate McHugh\nlined a single to left. The Bluejay DH stole second and raced home on an RBI double by North.\nMiami took advantage of three Creighton walks, a hit batter, a single and a three-run double in the seventh to take a commanding 9-4 edge and went on to win the game by that score.\nReliever\nJT Adams\ntook the loss (1-1), allowing two runs in the seventh in 0.1 innings. Miami reliever Lyndon Glidewell picked up the win, getting the final out of the seventh.\nThe Bluejays and Hurricanes continue their three-game set on Saturday, March 21 at 5:00 pm (CT).",
